{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3dcf609f-19b3-470d-aa13-367bbaf5793d","content":"In .NET MAUI, you use the **lifecycle event mapping** in `MauiProgram.cs` via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;\n\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android =>\n    {\n        android.OnPause(activity => { /* your code */ });\n        android.OnStop(activity => { /* your code */ });\n    });\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios =>\n    {\n        ios.DidEnterBackground(app => { /* your code */ });\n    });\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Add the `Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents` namespace.\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code separate.\n- Each handler receives the native object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS), giving you full platform API access.\n- Other events are available too (e.g., `OnResume`, `WillEnterForeground`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b8d02fe9-dabf-422a-8203-16109cc2abd2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI — specifically Android's OnPause/OnStop and iOS's DidEnterBackground. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development, not a codebase-specific task.","outputTokens":355,"requestId":"DBCF:31910B:98481:BF6FA:69F54AB4"},"id":"d9aeed6a-d9d5-4948-ade1-5c48e22302ff","timestamp":"2026-05-02T00:52:12.678Z","parentId":"8a37471f-5d8a-46a4-84b7-2776bee17b92"}
